{"title_page": "TANS Per\u00fa Flight 204", "text_new": "{{Infobox Aircraft occurrence\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|name = TANS Per\u00fa Flight 204\n|image = TANS Per\u00fa Boeing 737-200Adv OB-1809 LIM 2005-8-3.png\n|image_size = 230 |alt = \n|caption = OB-1809-P, the aircraft involved, photographed in August 2005.\n|date = 23 August 2005\n|type = [[Pilot error]]\n|site = [[Pucallpa]], Peru\n|coordinates = {{coord|8|25|0|S|74|35|45|W|type:event|display=inline,title}}<ref name=\"Final report\"/>{{rp|6}}\n|occupants = 98\n|passengers = 91\n|crew = 7\n|fatalities = 40\n|survivors = 58\n|aircraft_type = [[Boeing 737-200 Advanced|Boeing 737-244 Advanced]]\n|IATA = TJ204\n|ICAO = ELV204\n|callsign = Aereos Selva 204\n|tail_number = OB-1809-P\n|operator = [[TANS Per\u00fa]]\n|origin = [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport|Jorge Ch\u00e1vez Int'l Airport]]<br />[[Lima]], Peru\n|stopover = [[Captain Rolden International Airport|Captain Rolden Int'l Airport]]<br />[[Pucallpa]], Peru\n|destination = {{nowrap|[[Coronel FAP Francisco Secada Vignetta International Airport|Crnl. FAP F. S. Vignetta Int'l Airport]]<br />[[Iquitos]], Peru}}\n}}\n\n'''TANS Per\u00fa Flight 204''' refers to a domestic scheduled [[Lima]]\u2013[[Pucallpa]]\u2013[[Iquitos]] passenger service, operated with a [[Boeing 737-200 Advanced]], that crashed on 23 August 2005 on approach to [[Pucallpa Airport]], {{convert|4|mi}} off the airfield, following an [[emergency landing]] attempt because of bad weather, killing 40 of the 98 passengers and crew aboard.\n\n==Aircraft and crew==\nThe aircraft involved was a 1981-built [[Boeing 737-200 Advanced|Boeing 737-244 Advanced]], [[Aircraft registration|registered]] OB-1809, which had been [[Aircraft lease|lease]]d to TANS Per\u00fa from the South African lessor company [[Safair]] two months prior to the accident.<ref name=\"TANS confirms 57 survivors in 737-200 crash\" /> With [[manufacturer's serial number]] 22580 and powered with two [[Pratt & Whitney JT8D|Pratt & Whitney JT8D-17A]] engines, the airframe had its maiden flight on 4 August 1981, and was originally delivered to [[South African Airways]].<ref name=\"ASN\">{{ASN accident|id= 20050823-0|accessdate= 16 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b737-22580.htm|title=TANS OB-1809-P aircraft history|last=|first=|date=|website=Airfleets.net|publisher=Airfleets aviation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> At the time of the accident the aircraft had accumulated 49,865 flight hours and 45,262 cycles,<ref name=\"Final report\"/> and was {{Age|1981|8|4|2005|8|23}} years old.\n\nThe captain was 45-year-old Octavio Perez Palma Garreta, who had 5,867 flight hours, including 3,763 hours on the Boeing 737. The first officer was 37-year-old Jorge Luis Pinto Panta, who had 4,755 flight hours, with 1,109 of them on the Boeing 737. 38-year-old Gonzalo Chirinos Delgado, a trainee pilot, was also on board. He had 2,700 flight hours, but only 61 of them on the Boeing 737.<ref name=\"TANS confirms 57 survivors in 737-200 crash\" />{{Rp|7\u201310}}\n\n==Description of the accident==\nThere was an unusual developing [[cold front]] in the vicinity of Pucallpa, minutes before the event took place, with [[cloud top]]s estimated to be {{convert|45000|ft}} high.<ref name=\"Final report\"/> Instead of diverting to another airport, the crew initiated the approach to Pucallpa Airport with torrential rain, hail and strong winds.<ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\"/> Some {{cardinal to word|10}} minutes before the scheduled time for landing the aircraft started rocking.<ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\"/> Realising that the airport could not be safely reached amid the worsening weather conditions, the pilot attempted an emergency landing. The aircraft was flying through a [[hail]]storm for the last 32 seconds of its ill-fated flight when it was seemingly taken down by a wind shear, hit tree tops, impacted terrain in a [[swamp]] located {{convert|3.8|nmi}} ahead of the [[runway]] threshold, broke up as it [[Emergency landing|crash landed]] and burst into flames, leaving a path of debris and flaming fuel {{convert|100|ft}} wide and {{convert|0.8|nmi}} long.<ref name=\"Final report\"/><ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\"/> The wreckage of the airplane was engulfed by the fire.<ref name=\"Final report\"/>\n\nThere were 91 passengers and seven [[Aircrew|crew member]]s on board; {{cardinal|35}} passengers and {{cardinal to word|5}} crew (including all three flight crew) lost their lives in the accident.<ref name=\"Final report\" />{{rp|7}} Non-[[Peru]]vian occupants of the aircraft included 11 [[Americans]], one Australian, one Colombian, and one [[Spain|Spaniard]]; Italians were also aboard, but the actual figures for them depend upon the source.<ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\" /><ref name=\"Plane crashes in Peruvian jungle\">{{cite news|title=Plane crashes in Peruvian jungle |work=[[BBC News]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/4178868.stm |date=24 August 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67aNlpfwj?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/4178868.stm |archivedate=11 May 2012 |accessdate=11 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Most of the fatalities were recorded for passengers travelling in the front of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Final report\" /> Fifty-eight people survived the accident, many of them suffering serious injuries, mostly burns and broken limbs.<ref name=\"Final report\"/><ref name=\"Plane crashes in Peruvian jungle\"/>\n\n==Investigation==\nInvestigation of the crash site was hindered by looters, who descended upon the crash and stole various elements to be sold for scrap.<ref name=\"Escape from flight 204\" /> A {{US$|500|2005|link=yes}} reward did succeed in securing the return of the [[flight data recorder]].<ref name=\"Data recorder from Peru plane crash found\" /> After 312 days of investigations, there were no reports of any technical malfunction.<ref name=\"Final report\"/><ref name=\"ASN\"/> The official cause of the accident was determined to be [[pilot error]] for not following standard procedures under adverse weather conditions.<ref name=\"Final report\"/> The captain took control of the plane, but the trainee pilot did not immediately monitor the instruments; as a result, the crew did not notice the rapid descent in the few crucial seconds they had where they could have avoided danger.  According to [[Aviation Safety Network]], the accident ranks among the deadliest ones that took place in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title= Accident record for 2005|work= Aviation Safety Network|accessdate= 11 May 2012|url= http://aviation-safety.net/database/dblist.php?Year=2005&lang=&page=1}}</ref> It was also the second major crash involving a TANS Per\u00fa airplane in slightly over two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/operator/airline.php?var=4736|title=Accident record for TANS Per\u00fa|last=Ranter|first=Harro|date=|work=aviation-safety.net|publisher=Aviation Safety Network|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/world/americas/24iht-web.0824peru.html|title=At least 41 dead in Peruvian plane crash|date=24 August 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=11 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67aUXB0iB?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/world/americas/24iht-web.0824peru.html?_r=1|archivedate=11 May 2012|publisher=Associated Press|location=[[Lima]]|issn=0362-4331|quote=In January 2003, a TANS twin engine Fokker 28 turbojet, plowed into a 11,550-foot (3,465-meter) high mountain in Peru's northern jungle, killing all 42 passengers \u2013 including eight children \u2013 and four crew members aboard.|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\nFlight 204 has been the subject of a ''Reader's Digest'' story and an [[MSNBC]] documentary.<ref name=\"Escape from flight 204\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rd.com/content/jet-crash-in-the-jungle/|title=Jet Crash in the Jungle|last=Rosellini|first=Lynn|date=January 2007|website=[[Reader's Digest]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117190121/http://www.rd.com/content/jet-crash-in-the-jungle/|archive-date=17 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Canadian TV series, ''[[Mayday (Canadian TV series)|Mayday]]'', has also produced an episode about the accident named \u2033Lack of Vision\u2033.<ref name=\"Mayday\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Peru|Aviation}}\n* [[Delta Air Lines Flight 191]], another incident involving wind shear\n* [[American Airlines Flight 965]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Lauda Air Flight 004]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Garuda Indonesia Flight 152]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Vietnam Airlines Flight 815]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Southern Airways Flight 242]], another incident involving hail\n* [[Pan Am Flight 759]]\n* [[TANS Per\u00fa Flight 222]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Data recorder from Peru plane crash found\">{{cite news|title= Data recorder from Peru plane crash found|newspaper= [[ChinaDaily]]|date= 31 August 2005|url= http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-08/31/content_473921.htm|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140627121918/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-08/31/content_473921.htm|archivedate= 27 June 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Escape from flight 204\">{{cite news|title=Escape from flight 204 |first=Victoria |last=Corderi |work=NBC News |date=30 September 2005 |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/9545549 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Final report\">{{cite web|title=OB-1809P Final Report |language=Spanish |url=http://www.mtc.gob.pe/portal/transportes/aereo/ciaa/2005/OB-1809P.pdf |accessdate=16 December 2011 |pages=68 |date=July 2006 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67ZOn3rf1?url=http://www.mtc.gob.pe/portal/transportes/aereo/ciaa/2005/OB-1809P.pdf |archivedate=11 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Mayday\">{{cite web|title= Mayday Season 12, Episode 5: Lack of Vision|url= http://www.discovery.ca/episodeList.aspx?sid=12966|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140627124538/http://www.discovery.ca/episodeList.aspx?sid=12966|archivedate= 27 June 2014 |quote= Investigators face a major challenge when looters make off with the Flight Data Recorder from the crash of TANS Peru Flight 204. Wreckage allows investigators to rule out engine failure. But with no FDR, it will take all their ingenuity to reconstruct the final moments of the flight and figure out why the 737 crashed into the jungle, just 4 kilometers short of the runway.}}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"TANS confirms 57 survivors in 737-200 crash\">{{cite news|title=TANS confirms 57 survivors in 737-200 crash |first=Kerry |last=Ezard |location=Washington D.C. |agency=[[Flight International]] |work=[[Flightglobal]] |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/tans-confirms-57-survivors-in-737-200-crash-201179/ |date=25 August 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67aNNH8Kv?url=http://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/tans-confirms-57-survivors-in-737-200-crash-201179/ |archivedate=11 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\">{{cite news|title=58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-08-23-peru-crash_x.htm |date=25 August 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67aNHBSYW?url=http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2005-08-23-peru-crash_x.htm |archivedate=11 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--\n<ref>{{cite news|title= At Least 37 Killed as Peruvian Jetliner Crashes|url= http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F00915FF355A0C778EDDA10894DD404482|work= [[The New York Times]]|date= 24 August 2005|accessdate= 16 December 2011}}</ref>\n<ref>http://www.airdisaster.com/cgi-bin/view_details.cgi?date=08232005&reg=OB-1809&airline=TANS+Peru</ref>\n-->\n*{{cite news|title= In pictures: Peru plane crash|work= [[BBC News]]|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_pictures/4179294.stm|date= 24 August 2005|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140627125307/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/in_pictures/4179294.stm|archivedate= 27 June 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;\n*{{cite news|title= Dozens Killed in Crash of Airliner in Peru Jungle|first= Carla|last= Salazar|agency= [[Associated Press]]|work= [[The Washington Post]]|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/08/23/AR2005082301409_pf.html|date= 24 August 2005|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://www.webcitation.org/6QdzGCjyg?url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/08/23/AR2005082301409_pf.html|archivedate= 27 June 2014|df= dmy-all}}&nbsp;\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in Peru}}\n{{Aviation incidents and accidents in 2005}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tans Peru Flight 204}}\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents caused by weather]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 2005]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in Peru]]\n[[Category:Airliner accidents and incidents caused by pilot error]]\n[[Category:Accidents and incidents involving the Boeing 737 Original]]\n[[Category:2005 meteorology]]\n[[Category:August 2005 events in South America]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Aircraft occurrence\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|name = TANS Per\u00fa Flight 204\n|image = TANS Per\u00fa Boeing 737-200Adv OB-1809 LIM 2005-8-3.png\n|image_size = 230 |alt = \n|caption = OB-1809-P, the aircraft involved, photographed in August 2005.\n|date = 23 August 2005\n|type = [[Pilot error]] in bad weather\n|site = [[Pucallpa]], Peru\n|coordinates = {{coord|8|25|0|S|74|35|45|W|type:event|display=inline,title}}<ref name=\"Final report\"/>{{rp|6}}\n|occupants = 98\n|passengers = 91\n|crew = 7\n|fatalities = 40\n|survivors = 58\n|aircraft_type = [[Boeing 737-200 Advanced|Boeing 737-244 Advanced]]\n|IATA = TJ204\n|ICAO = ELV204\n|callsign = Aereos Selva 204\n|tail_number = OB-1809-P\n|operator = [[TANS Per\u00fa]]\n|origin = [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport|Jorge Ch\u00e1vez Int'l Airport]]<br />[[Lima]], Peru\n|stopover = [[Captain Rolden International Airport|Captain Rolden Int'l Airport]]<br />[[Pucallpa]], Peru\n|destination = {{nowrap|[[Coronel FAP Francisco Secada Vignetta International Airport|Crnl. FAP F. S. Vignetta Int'l Airport]]<br />[[Iquitos]], Peru}}\n}}\n\n'''TANS Per\u00fa Flight 204''' refers to a domestic scheduled [[Lima]]\u2013[[Pucallpa]]\u2013[[Iquitos]] passenger service, operated with a [[Boeing 737-200 Advanced]], that crashed on 23 August 2005 on approach to [[Pucallpa Airport]], {{convert|4|mi}} off the airfield, following an [[emergency landing]] attempt because of bad weather, killing 40 of the 98 passengers and crew aboard.\n\n==Aircraft and crew==\nThe aircraft involved was a 1981-built [[Boeing 737-200 Advanced|Boeing 737-244 Advanced]], [[Aircraft registration|registered]] OB-1809, which had been [[Aircraft lease|lease]]d to TANS Per\u00fa from the South African lessor company [[Safair]] two months prior to the accident.<ref name=\"TANS confirms 57 survivors in 737-200 crash\" /> With [[manufacturer's serial number]] 22580 and powered with two [[Pratt & Whitney JT8D|Pratt & Whitney JT8D-17A]] engines, the airframe had its maiden flight on 4 August 1981, and was originally delivered to [[South African Airways]].<ref name=\"ASN\">{{ASN accident|id= 20050823-0|accessdate= 16 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b737-22580.htm|title=TANS OB-1809-P aircraft history|last=|first=|date=|website=Airfleets.net|publisher=Airfleets aviation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=24 October 2011}}</ref> At the time of the accident the aircraft had accumulated 49,865 flight hours and 45,262 cycles,<ref name=\"Final report\"/> and was {{Age|1981|8|4|2005|8|23}} years old.\n\nThe captain was 45-year-old Octavio Perez Palma Garreta, who had 5,867 flight hours, including 3,763 hours on the Boeing 737. The first officer was 37-year-old Jorge Luis Pinto Panta, who had 4,755 flight hours, with 1,109 of them on the Boeing 737. 38-year-old Gonzalo Chirinos Delgado, a trainee pilot, was also on board. He had 2,700 flight hours, but only 61 of them on the Boeing 737.<ref name=\"TANS confirms 57 survivors in 737-200 crash\" />{{Rp|7\u201310}}\n\n==Description of the accident==\nThere was an unusual developing [[cold front]] in the vicinity of Pucallpa, minutes before the event took place, with [[cloud top]]s estimated to be {{convert|45000|ft}} high.<ref name=\"Final report\"/> Instead of diverting to another airport, the crew initiated the approach to Pucallpa Airport with torrential rain, hail and strong winds.<ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\"/> Some {{cardinal to word|10}} minutes before the scheduled time for landing the aircraft started rocking.<ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\"/> Realising that the airport could not be safely reached amid the worsening weather conditions, the pilot attempted an emergency landing. The aircraft was flying through a [[hail]]storm for the last 32 seconds of its ill-fated flight when it was seemingly taken down by a wind shear, hit tree tops, impacted terrain in a [[swamp]] located {{convert|3.8|nmi}} ahead of the [[runway]] threshold, broke up as it [[Emergency landing|crash landed]] and burst into flames, leaving a path of debris and flaming fuel {{convert|100|ft}} wide and {{convert|0.8|nmi}} long.<ref name=\"Final report\"/><ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\"/> The wreckage of the airplane was engulfed by the fire.<ref name=\"Final report\"/>\n\nThere were 91 passengers and seven [[Aircrew|crew member]]s on board; {{cardinal|35}} passengers and {{cardinal to word|5}} crew (including all three flight crew) lost their lives in the accident.<ref name=\"Final report\" />{{rp|7}} Non-[[Peru]]vian occupants of the aircraft included 11 [[Americans]], one Australian, one Colombian, and one [[Spain|Spaniard]]; Italians were also aboard, but the actual figures for them depend upon the source.<ref name=\"58 walk away from Peruvian plane crash\" /><ref name=\"Plane crashes in Peruvian jungle\">{{cite news|title=Plane crashes in Peruvian jungle |work=[[BBC News]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/4178868.stm |date=24 August 2005 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67aNlpfwj?url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/4178868.stm |archivedate=11 May 2012 |accessdate=11 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> Most of the fatalities were recorded for passengers travelling in the front of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Final report\" /> Fifty-eight people survived the accident, many of them suffering serious injuries, mostly burns and broken limbs.<ref name=\"Final report\"/><ref name=\"Plane crashes in Peruvian jungle\"/>\n\n==Investigation==\nInvestigation of the crash site was hindered by looters, who descended upon the crash and stole various elements to be sold for scrap.<ref name=\"Escape from flight 204\" /> A {{US$|500|2005|link=yes}} reward did succeed in securing the return of the [[flight data recorder]].<ref name=\"Data recorder from Peru plane crash found\" /> After 312 days of investigations, there were no reports of any technical malfunction.<ref name=\"Final report\"/><ref name=\"ASN\"/> The official cause of the accident was determined to be [[pilot error]] for not following standard procedures under adverse weather conditions.<ref name=\"Final report\"/> The captain took control of the plane, but the trainee pilot did not immediately monitor the instruments; as a result, the crew did not notice the rapid descent in the few crucial seconds they had where they could have avoided danger. According to [[Aviation Safety Network]], the accident ranks among the deadliest ones that took place in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|title= Accident record for 2005|work= Aviation Safety Network|accessdate= 11 May 2012|url= http://aviation-safety.net/database/dblist.php?Year=2005&lang=&page=1}}</ref> It was also the second major crash involving a TANS Per\u00fa airplane in slightly over two years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/operator/airline.php?var=4736|title=Accident record for TANS Per\u00fa|last=Ranter|first=Harro|date=|work=aviation-safety.net|publisher=Aviation Safety Network|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/world/americas/24iht-web.0824peru.html|title=At least 41 dead in Peruvian plane crash|date=24 August 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=11 May 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67aUXB0iB?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/world/americas/24iht-web.0824peru.html?_r=1|archivedate=11 May 2012|publisher=Associated Press|location=[[Lima]]|issn=0362-4331|quote=In January 2003, a TANS twin engine Fokker 28 turbojet, plowed into a 11,550-foot (3,465-meter) high mountain in Peru's northern jungle, killing all 42 passengers \u2013 including eight children \u2013 and four crew members aboard.|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n== In the media ==\nFlight 204 has been the subject of a ''Reader's Digest'' story and an [[MSNBC]] documentary.<ref name=\"Escape from flight 204\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rd.com/content/jet-crash-in-the-jungle/|title=Jet Crash in the Jungle|last=Rosellini|first=Lynn|date=January 2007|website=[[Reader's Digest]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071117190121/http://www.rd.com/content/jet-crash-in-the-jungle/|archive-date=17 November 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Canadian TV series, ''[[Mayday (Canadian TV series)|Mayday]]'', has also produced an episode about the accident named \u2033Lack of Vision\u2033.<ref name=\"Mayday\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Peru|Aviation}}\n* [[Delta Air Lines Flight 191]], another incident involving wind shear\n* [[American Airlines Flight 965]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Lauda Air Flight 004]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Garuda Indonesia Flight 152]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Vietnam Airlines Flight 815]], another event involving looters at the crash site\n* [[Southern Airways Flight 242]], another incident involving hail\n* [[Pan Am Flight 759]]\n* [[TANS Per\u00fa Flight 222]]\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Data recorder from Peru plane crash found\">{{cite news|title= Data recorder from Peru plane crash found|newspaper= [[ChinaDaily]]|date= 31 August 2005|url= http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-08/31/content_473921.htm|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140627121918/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-08/31/content_473921.htm|archivedate= 27 June 2014 }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Escape from flight 204\">{{cite news|title=Escape from flight 204 |first=Victoria |last=Corderi |work=NBC News |date=30 September 2005 |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/9545549 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Final report\">{{cite web|title=OB-1809P Final Report |language=Spanish |url=http://www.mtc.gob.pe/portal/transportes/aereo/ciaa/2005/OB-1809P.pdf |accessdate=16 December 2011 |pages=68 |date=July 2006 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67ZOn3rf1?url=http://www.mtc.gob.pe/portal/transportes/aereo/ciaa/2005/OB-1809P.pdf |archivedate=11 May 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n<!-- + -->\n<ref name=\"Mayday\">{{cite web|title= Mayday Season 12, Episode 5: L